The length $\blue{l}$ of the rectangle is $\blue{15}$. The height $\green{h}$ of the rectangle is $\green{7.5}$. The radius $\pink{r}$ is half the diameter, so the radius is $\pink{r}=\pink{7.5}\text{ cm}$. 

$\begin{align}\qquad \dfrac{{\text{Area of Rectangle}}}{{\text{Area of Semicircle}}} &= \dfrac{\blue{l}\cdot\green{h}}{0.5\pi\pink{r}^2}\\\\&= \dfrac{\blue{15\cdot}\green{7.5}}{0.5\pi\pink{7.5}^2}\\\\&= \dfrac{2\gray{\cancel{\blue{15}}}\cdot\cancel{\green{7.5}}}{{0.5}\pi\gray{\cancel{\pink{{7.5}}}}^\cancel{2}}\\\\&=  \dfrac{4}{\pi}
 \end{align}$

The length $\blue{l}$ of the rectangle is $\blue{12}$. The height $\green{h}$ of the rectangle is $\green{8}$. The radius $\pink{r}$ is half the diameter, so the radius is $\pink{r}=\pink{6}\text{ cm}$. 

$\begin{align}\qquad \dfrac{{\text{Area of Rectangle}}}{{\text{Area of Semicirle}}} &= \dfrac{\blue{l}\cdot\green{h}}{0.5\pi\pink{r}^2}\\\\&= \dfrac{\blue{12\cdot}\green{8}}{0.5\pi\pink{6}^2}\\\\&=  \dfrac{16}{3\pi}
 \end{align}$

Let's substitute $\blue{N=8100}$ and $\red{t=4}$ into the formula and evaluate.  

$\begin{align*}
\blue{8100} \cdot \left(\frac{2}{3} \right)^{\red{4}} 
 & =\blue{8100} \left(\frac{2\cdot 2\cdot 2\cdot 2}{3\cdot 3\cdot 3\cdot 3}\right) \\
\\
 & =\blue{8100} \left(\frac{16}{81}\right)  \\
 & =\frac{8100 \cdot 16}{81} 
=\frac{\cancel{81} \cdot 100 \cdot 16}{\cancel{81}}  \\[1mm]
 & = 1600
\end{align*}$

Let's substitute $\red{t=3}$ and $\blue{N=64000}$ into the formula and evaluate.

$\begin{align*}
\blue{64000} \cdot \left(\frac{1}{2} \right)^{\red{3}} 
 & =\blue{64000} \left(\frac{1\cdot1\cdot1}{2\cdot 2\cdot 2}\right) \\
 & =\blue{64000} \left(\frac{1}{8}\right)  \\
 & =\frac{64 \cdot 1000 }{8} 
=\frac{8\cdot\cancel{8} \cdot 1000}{\cancel{8}}  \\[1mm]
 & = 8000
\end{align*}$

Let's now use this formula to calculate the length of line that remains after Georg repeats the eraser procedure $\purple{n=4}$ times starting from a line with length $\gray{\ell}=\gray{9}\text{ cm}$.

The length of line remaining is given by the expression:


$\begin{align*}
\gray{\ell}\cdot\left(\blue{\frac{2}{3}} \right)^{\purple{n}}
 &=\gray{9}\cdot\left(\blue{\frac{2}{3}}\right)^{\purple{4}}  \\[1mm]
 &= \gray{9}\cdot\left(\frac{2\cdot 2\cdot 2\cdot 2}{3\cdot 3\cdot 3\cdot 3}\right)  \\[1mm]
 &= \gray{9} \cdot \dfrac{16}{81}  \\[1mm]
 &=  \dfrac{16}{9}
\end{align*}$

$3.14, 3.141, 3.1415,$ and $3.14159$ are all terminating decimals, so they are rational numbers.  We can also see that they're rational because they can be represented as fractions:

$3.14=3\dfrac{14}{100}=\dfrac{314}{100}$ ;

$3.141=3\dfrac{141}{1000}=\dfrac{3141}{1000}$ ;

$3.1415=3\dfrac{1415}{10{,}000}=\dfrac{31{,}415}{10{,}000}$ ; and

$3.14159=3\dfrac{14{,}159}{100{,}000}=\dfrac{314{,}159}{100{,}000}$ .

Let's substitute $\red{r=20}$ and $\blue{b=10}$ into the formula $\dfrac{\blue{b}}{ \blue{b}+\red{r}}\,$ and evaluate.

$\begin{align*}
\dfrac{\blue{b}}{ \blue{b}+\red{r}}
 &=\dfrac{\blue{10}}{ \blue{10}+\red{20}} \\[2mm]
 &=\dfrac{10}{ 30 } = \dfrac{1\cdot 10}{ 3 \cdot 10 } \\[1mm]
 &= \dfrac{1 \cdot \green{\cancel{10}}}{3 \cdot \green{\cancel{10}} } \\[1mm]
 &=\dfrac{1}{3}
\end{align*}$

Let's now carry out the fraction calculation, step by step:  

$\qquad\begin{align*}
\blue{2}\times\purple{2\!\frac{3}{4}} 
&= \blue{2}\times\purple{\frac{11}{4}}  \\[2mm]
&= \frac{2\times11}{4}   \\[2mm]
&=  \frac{22}{4} \\[1mm]
&= \frac{11}{2} \\[1mm]
&= \green{5\!\dfrac{1}{2}}
\end{align*}$

For two loaves, Marin will need $\green{5\!\dfrac{1}{2}}$ cups of water.

Let's now carry out the fraction calculation step by step:  

$\qquad\begin{align*}
\blue{3}\times\purple{2\!\frac{1}{4}} 
&= \blue{3}\times\left(\purple{2} \ + \purple{\frac{1}{4}}\right)  \\[2mm]
&= \blue{3}\times\purple{2} + \blue{3}\times\purple{\frac{1}{4}} \\[1mm]
&=\ \ \ 6  \quad + \quad \frac{3}{4} \ \ \\[1mm]
&= \green{6\!\dfrac{3}{4}}
\end{align*}$

For three portions, Marianne will need $\green{6\!\dfrac{3}{4}}$ cups of flour.

Let's add together the angle measures $\blue{40}^\circ$,  $\blue{60}^\circ$, and $\blue{90}^\circ$:

$\begin{align}
\,\text{Sum of angle measures} 
 &=  \blue{40^\circ}+\blue{60^\circ}+\blue{90^\circ}\\
&= 190^\circ.\end{align}$

The sum of the three angles is greater than $\pink{180^\circ}$.
